📘 Subject: General Studies Paper I (Prelims – Polity)
🧠 Topic: Fundamental Rights (Part III of the Constitution)

(One of the most important topics for UPSC Prelims & Mains.)

1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 Meaning of Fundamental Rights

Fundamental Rights are basic rights guaranteed by the Constitution to all citizens to ensure:

Freedom

Equality

Justice

Protection from arbitrary state action

📌 Mentioned in Part III of the Constitution (Articles 12–35).

Inspired by the US Bill of Rights.

🔵 Six Fundamental Rights

Originally 7 rights, but Right to Property removed by 44th Amendment (1978).

Now 6 Fundamental Rights remain:

Right	Articles
Right to Equality	14–18
Right to Freedom	19–22
Right against Exploitation	23–24
Right to Freedom of Religion	25–28
Cultural & Educational Rights	29–30
Right to Constitutional Remedies	32
🔹 Right to Equality (Articles 14–18)

Includes:

Equality before law

Prohibition of discrimination

Equal opportunity in public employment

Abolition of untouchability

Abolition of titles

📌 Article 17 abolishes untouchability.

🔹 Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22)

Includes freedoms such as:

Speech and expression

Assembly

Association

Movement

Residence

Profession

📌 Article 21: Right to Life and Personal Liberty

One of the most important articles.

🔹 Right Against Exploitation (Articles 23–24)

Prohibits:

Human trafficking

Forced labour

Child labour in hazardous industries

🔹 Freedom of Religion (Articles 25–28)

India is a secular state.

People can:

Practice religion

Propagate religion

Manage religious affairs

🔹 Cultural & Educational Rights (Articles 29–30)

Protect rights of:

Minorities

Linguistic groups

Cultural communities

Allows minorities to establish educational institutions.

🔴 Right to Constitutional Remedies (Article 32)

Allows citizens to move the Supreme Court for protection of rights.

Dr. B.R. Ambedkar called it:

👉 “Heart and Soul of the Constitution.”

🔹 Types of Writs

Supreme Court and High Courts can issue writs:

1️⃣ Habeas Corpus
2️⃣ Mandamus
3️⃣ Prohibition
4️⃣ Certiorari
5️⃣ Quo Warranto

